01:07.358 --> 01:08.401
Hey, pal! Hey.

01:09.194 --> 01:11.404
Hey, hey, hey! Pal!

01:19.704 --> 01:24.334
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- (CUTLERY CLATTERING)

01:35.178 --> 01:40.850
♪ (TENSE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

02:33.611 --> 02:35.363
- (MEN CHUCKLE)
- (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

02:35.363 --> 02:37.657
GUEST 1: Fire!
Fire in the kitchen!

02:37.657 --> 02:40.451
- GUEST 2: Fire! Fire!
- (FIRE ALARM BLARING)

02:40.451 --> 02:45.623
- ♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
- (INDISTINCT CLAMOR)

02:54.799 --> 03:00.263
(INDISTINCT CLAMOR)

03:14.986 --> 03:18.406
(SHIP HORN BLARING IN DISTANCE)

03:38.635 --> 03:44.182
♪ (SOFT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

03:46.267 --> 03:48.645
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

03:52.148 --> 03:53.566
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

04:02.200 --> 04:05.578
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

04:58.006 --> 04:59.007
(SNIFFS)

05:10.184 --> 05:16.816
♪ (JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

05:19.986 --> 05:23.281
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

05:25.116 --> 05:26.284
Morning, Walt.

05:31.831 --> 05:32.999
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

05:41.924 --> 05:43.426
(MARION KANG GASPS)

05:43.426 --> 05:44.427
Who are you?

05:44.427 --> 05:45.762
MARION: Good morning, Mr. Mason.

05:45.762 --> 05:48.222
I'm Marion Kang,
your new secretary.

05:48.222 --> 05:51.601
- My what?
- Would you mind signing in?

05:51.601 --> 05:53.352
Bronson Secretarial School
taught us

05:53.352 --> 05:55.980
it's of the utmost importance
to keep a record of who...

05:55.980 --> 05:58.316
DELLA STREET:
Yes, I hired a secretary.

05:58.316 --> 06:00.193
Because as I've said forever,
we need someone

06:00.193 --> 06:02.111
to answer the phone, take notes,
keep the books.

06:02.111 --> 06:04.113
- We couldn't even afford--
- DELLA: And if I'm out there

06:04.113 --> 06:05.198
doing Marion's job,

06:05.198 --> 06:07.325
well, I can't be in here
with you doing mine.

06:07.325 --> 06:08.659
That was our deal.

06:08.659 --> 06:10.578
I'm in here with a seat
at the table.

06:10.578 --> 06:12.163
Well, you're gonna have
to sell the table

06:12.163 --> 06:13.206
to pay for her.

06:13.206 --> 06:14.916
The last of EB's debts
were paid off

06:14.916 --> 06:16.209
on the first of this month.

06:16.209 --> 06:18.169
And what's left over
from what you contributed

06:18.169 --> 06:20.755
from the sale of the farm,
plus our current clients,

06:20.755 --> 06:22.173
- such as they are...
- (KNOCK ON DOOR)

06:22.173 --> 06:25.760
DELLA: ...we have-- Come in.
Just enough to pay the monthly,

06:25.760 --> 06:28.012
plus pay for a secretary.

06:30.014 --> 06:31.474
Thank you.

06:31.474 --> 06:33.267
DELLA: The house is
in Mr. Burkhardt's name,

06:33.267 --> 06:35.561
so we'll need to refile it
to joint ownership,

06:35.561 --> 06:37.772
so it will go directly
to Mrs. Burkhardt

06:37.772 --> 06:39.273
if he passes away first.

06:39.273 --> 06:41.275
And all proceeds
from the second survivor

06:41.275 --> 06:44.278
will be split equally
among their three children,

06:44.278 --> 06:46.322
Theobald, Bruna, and Engleberta.

06:46.322 --> 06:47.657
Beautiful names.

06:47.657 --> 06:50.952
I'm sure none of them have tried
to boil a child in a fairy tale.

06:50.952 --> 06:53.162
DELLA: Bruna will be bequeathed
the table clock

06:53.162 --> 06:54.288
and the swan vase.

06:54.288 --> 06:57.208
Engleberta and her mother's
daisy brooch.

06:57.208 --> 06:59.836
Theobald, his father's
beer stein collection.

06:59.836 --> 07:03.256
Oh, Theobald, you are
one lucky son of a bitch.

07:04.382 --> 07:05.842
- Hey.
- PERRY MASON: What?

07:05.842 --> 07:07.677
(SCOFFS) Can we focus, please?

07:09.470 --> 07:10.847
- I am.
- DELLA: You're the one

07:10.847 --> 07:14.183
who suddenly wanted to give up
criminal law and only do civil.

07:14.183 --> 07:16.144
- This is civil.
- You're the one who said

07:16.144 --> 07:17.728
civil work kept firms
in business.

07:17.728 --> 07:19.814
- I'm just being practical.
- Since when?

07:19.814 --> 07:21.941
- What time is court tomorrow?
- DELLA: Nine.

07:23.234 --> 07:24.360
Nine a.m.

07:25.486 --> 07:26.404
Practical.

07:26.404 --> 07:28.573
A practical person
would own a date book.

07:28.573 --> 07:29.699
- I don't need one.
- (KNOCK ON DOOR)

07:29.699 --> 07:31.117
- I have a secretary.
- (DOOR OPENING)

07:33.411 --> 07:35.705
- MARION: These came for you.
- Thank you.

07:35.705 --> 07:36.998
DELLA: Thank you, Marion.

07:36.998 --> 07:40.209
- (FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)
- (DOOR CLOSING)

07:40.209 --> 07:46.757
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

07:50.011 --> 07:52.597
(GASPS, COUGHS)

07:52.597 --> 07:54.223
BROOKS MCCUTCHEON:
Doing all right?

07:56.601 --> 07:57.643
(GASPS)

07:59.312 --> 08:02.190
- Hey.
- (BREATHES SHAKILY)

08:02.190 --> 08:03.900
Thanks for being a good sport.

08:05.359 --> 08:07.320
Of course. (COUGHS)

08:08.613 --> 08:10.615
It was... (INHALES SHARPLY)

08:10.615 --> 08:12.658
- ...different. (COUGHS)
- (CHUCKLES)

08:16.412 --> 08:17.663
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

08:20.208 --> 08:23.044
I'm working on the boat tonight.
(CLEARS THROAT)

08:25.129 --> 08:26.172
Will you be there?

08:28.257 --> 08:29.383
Uh, maybe.

08:32.345 --> 08:33.596
(SIGHS) Listen...

08:34.680 --> 08:35.723
do me a favor.

08:36.891 --> 08:38.851
Wait ten minutes
after I leave...

08:40.353 --> 08:41.479
then you can go.

08:45.650 --> 08:47.652
(DOOR OPENING, CLOSING)

08:47.652 --> 08:50.404
- (SEAGULLS SQUAWKING)
- (WAVES CRASHING)

08:50.404 --> 08:56.327
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

08:56.327 --> 08:58.788
Old Fashioned
and a Reuben sandwich, George.

08:58.788 --> 08:59.914
GEORGE: Yes, sir.

09:03.167 --> 09:04.335
- Hey.
- You were done with it.

09:04.335 --> 09:05.920
You only read
the funnies anyway, Cliff.

09:05.920 --> 09:07.922
- ELIZABETH MCCUTCHEON:
Hi. (CHUCKLES)
- PHILLIP MCCUTCHEON: Dad!

09:07.922 --> 09:10.341
- Darling.
- ELIZABETH: Darling. (KISSES)

09:10.341 --> 09:12.218
- What'd you boys find?
- (CHUCKLES)

09:12.218 --> 09:13.761
- It's a seahorse!
- CHARLES MCCUTCHEON: Yeah.

09:13.761 --> 09:15.054
Oh, that is neat.

09:15.054 --> 09:18.182
I ordered the boys creamsicles.
Do you want one?

09:20.518 --> 09:22.520
Uh, I just ordered myself something.

09:22.520 --> 09:27.024
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

09:27.024 --> 09:29.485
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

09:31.946 --> 09:33.239
Hello, Father. (SIGHS)

09:33.239 --> 09:35.074
LYDELL MCCUTCHEON:
Where were you, Brooks?

09:37.576 --> 09:38.869
I've been here.

09:40.621 --> 09:42.957
Can't remember the last time
you came down to the club.

09:44.709 --> 09:47.837
The place never really
turned out how I envisioned

09:47.837 --> 09:49.255
when I started it.

09:50.256 --> 09:52.341
Though it is a beautiful view.

09:52.341 --> 09:55.511
Quite remarkable
just how far out into the ocean

09:55.511 --> 09:57.471
you can see boats from here.

10:01.309 --> 10:04.562
It wasn't supposed to be
that big of a deal.

10:04.562 --> 10:06.355
We were just trying
to sabotage the Luxe,

10:06.355 --> 10:07.857
not destroy it.

10:07.857 --> 10:10.109
And the fire got
a little out of control.

10:10.109 --> 10:12.695
Wouldn't it have been smarter
to sabotage it during the day

10:12.695 --> 10:15.531
when it's not packed
to the gills with witnesses?

10:16.949 --> 10:18.909
I'm sorry, Dad. I...

10:20.453 --> 10:22.496
- What can I say? I'll fix it.
- No.

10:22.496 --> 10:25.291
(SCOFFS) No more fixing, Brooks.

10:25.291 --> 10:27.710
It's over.
You need to step back.

10:27.710 --> 10:29.211
- But I just--
- LYDELL: Back from your position

10:29.211 --> 10:32.006
in the company. Back from
your gambling interest.

10:32.006 --> 10:34.842
Back from your bullshit
with the baseball team.

10:35.634 --> 10:38.054
The baseball team is coming.

10:38.054 --> 10:40.848
We-- We've got four cities
showing real interest.

10:40.848 --> 10:43.267
I'm close on this one, Dad.

10:43.267 --> 10:46.645
I'm really building
something meaningful.

10:46.645 --> 10:48.564
Building takes
a firm foundation, Brooks.

10:48.564 --> 10:50.191
Your dabbling
in every little folly

10:50.191 --> 10:51.692
is anything but that.

10:51.692 --> 10:53.361
It's as solid as a sandcastle.

11:00.743 --> 11:01.994
Did I tell you I got

11:01.994 --> 11:03.996
at least 20 companies that want
to advertise at the stadium?

11:03.996 --> 11:05.706
I've got Chesterfield,

11:05.706 --> 11:08.668
- uh, Goodyear--
- LYDELL: Brooks! Stop!

11:09.835 --> 11:11.504
Take my advice and walk away.

11:18.844 --> 11:21.597
♪ (SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

11:22.807 --> 11:25.142
LYDELL:
Spend time with your boys.

11:25.142 --> 11:28.020
Concentrate
on your charity work.

11:30.731 --> 11:33.025
That's a perfectly
admirable legacy.

11:34.318 --> 11:36.529
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

11:53.379 --> 11:54.505
(THUD)

11:58.926 --> 12:03.472
- (FAUCET SQUEAKING)
- ♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

12:03.472 --> 12:06.976
(WATER RUNNING)

12:36.046 --> 12:37.173
(GUN COCKS)

12:45.806 --> 12:46.807
Hey.

12:51.187 --> 12:52.313
Mr. Mason.

12:57.234 --> 12:59.028
How-- How did you get in here?

13:01.530 --> 13:04.241
Do you believe that I will?

13:05.034 --> 13:12.041
- What?
- (COUGHS, CHOKES)

13:12.917 --> 13:15.628
Do you be... that I... (CHOKES)

13:16.962 --> 13:19.048
- (COUGHS)
- Believe what?

13:19.048 --> 13:21.175
(COUGHS)

13:23.135 --> 13:27.056
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES, FADES) ♪

13:32.853 --> 13:33.938
(SIGHS)

13:41.403 --> 13:46.534
- (SIGHS)
- ♪ (SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

13:54.792 --> 13:56.544
(MOTORCYCLE ENGINE REVVING)

14:10.349 --> 14:13.519
EMILY DODSON: <i>"Dear Mr. Mason,
when will I be fully cleansed?</i>

14:13.519 --> 14:15.521
<i>I continue to ask God
for guidance,</i>

14:15.521 --> 14:17.398
<i>but I fear He is turning
His back on me."</i>

14:17.398 --> 14:19.733
<i>"Dear Mr. Mason,
what did we win in court?</i>

14:19.733 --> 14:22.736
<i>What's my freedom worth?
My boy Charlie is still gone."</i>

14:22.736 --> 14:24.238
<i>"Dear Mr. Mason,
today would've been</i>

14:24.238 --> 14:27.074
<i>Charlie's second birthday.
I desperately want to join him."</i>

14:27.074 --> 14:30.494
<i>"Dear Mr. Mason, do you believe
that I will be fully forgiven?"</i>

14:30.494 --> 14:32.871
<i>"Dear Mr. Mason--"
"Dear Mr. Mason..."</i>

14:40.546 --> 14:42.464
(GROANS)

14:57.271 --> 14:58.480
BAILIFF: All rise.

15:03.986 --> 15:05.696
JUDGE CARLISLE:
You may be seated.

15:09.908 --> 15:11.076
(DOOR OPENING)

15:17.333 --> 15:19.501
- PERRY: Sorry.
- Why are you limping?

15:20.085 --> 15:21.128
Hmm? I'm not.

15:25.090 --> 15:28.552
Mr. Purtell, exactly
how many years did you work

15:28.552 --> 15:29.762
at Sunny Market?

15:29.762 --> 15:32.598
Uh, seven years.
Three of those as a manager.

15:32.598 --> 15:36.018
And how would you say the owner,
Mr. Gryce, treated you?

15:36.018 --> 15:39.188
ED PURTELL: He was a tough boss.

15:39.188 --> 15:41.190
Uh, did your pay increase
very much

15:41.190 --> 15:42.358
when you became manager?

15:42.358 --> 15:43.651
- Barely.
- MR. KELLARD: And yet,

15:43.651 --> 15:45.653
you're the one
who helped design the layout

15:45.653 --> 15:46.987
of Mr. Gryce's stores,

15:46.987 --> 15:48.656
- isn't that right?
- That's right.

15:48.656 --> 15:49.907
MR. KELLARD: And since then,

15:49.907 --> 15:53.327
the stores have seen
an increase in sales

15:53.327 --> 15:58.374
of a staggering 60 percent,
even in these times.

15:58.374 --> 16:02.878
But did Mr. Gryce ever give you
credit for your design?

16:02.878 --> 16:05.381
Did he compensate you
in any way?

16:05.381 --> 16:07.591
No and no.

16:07.591 --> 16:09.968
- Did you talk to him about it?
- ED: I did.

16:09.968 --> 16:11.679
And he told me
if I didn't like it,

16:11.679 --> 16:13.222
I could take it on the arches.

16:13.222 --> 16:16.558
And that's exactly what you did.
And what did you do next?

16:16.558 --> 16:18.060
ED: I opened up my own store.

16:18.060 --> 16:20.646
MR. KELLARD:
You opened your own store.

16:20.646 --> 16:22.398
Pursued your dream.

16:22.398 --> 16:26.026
Followed the natural progression
of God-given capitalism

16:26.026 --> 16:28.862
and industriousness that makes
this country great!

16:28.862 --> 16:30.698
PERRY: Is there a question
in there, Your Honor,

16:30.698 --> 16:32.991
or does Mr. Kellard intend
to give all of his client's

16:32.991 --> 16:34.368
testimony himself?

16:34.368 --> 16:36.036
Mr. Kellard,
if you could limit yourself

16:36.036 --> 16:38.664
- to actual questions.
- Of course, Your Honor.

16:38.664 --> 16:42.251
It's just difficult
when I'm so proud

16:42.251 --> 16:44.586
to be representing
this fine man.

16:44.586 --> 16:46.672
Far be it for me to get
between two men in love,

16:46.672 --> 16:48.424
but that also didn't sound
like a question.

16:48.424 --> 16:49.717
- (PEOPLE LAUGH)
- JUDGE: And that's not

16:49.717 --> 16:52.010
a proper objection, Mr. Mason.

16:52.010 --> 16:54.722
Mr. Kellard, you may proceed
with your questioning.

16:57.349 --> 16:59.727
Why are you here today,
Mr. Purtell?

16:59.727 --> 17:03.439
Because Sunny Gryce is saying
I stole his ideas for my store.

17:03.439 --> 17:05.065
MR. KELLARD:
But you didn't steal anything,

17:05.065 --> 17:06.108
- did you?
- ED: How could I?

17:06.108 --> 17:07.484
They were my ideas
to begin with!

17:07.484 --> 17:09.528
Your ideas. Your methods.

17:09.528 --> 17:13.699
Your designs that Sunny Gryce
benefitted greatly from

17:13.699 --> 17:17.453
and is now claiming are his
and suing you in the process?

17:17.453 --> 17:19.121
He wants to put all
of the competition

17:19.121 --> 17:20.956
- out of business.
- Objection!

17:23.041 --> 17:26.587
Sorry. He-- He can't testify
to what our client wants.

17:27.588 --> 17:30.966
I got this. Uh, objection,
Y-- Your Honor,

17:30.966 --> 17:33.469
Mr. Purtell has no idea
what my client wants

17:33.469 --> 17:34.595
and does not want.

17:35.804 --> 17:37.097
Sustained.

17:37.097 --> 17:38.432
MR. KELLARD: Mr. Purtell...

17:40.809 --> 17:44.188
do you feel...

17:44.188 --> 17:48.233
that Sunny Gryce wants
to put you out of business?

17:48.233 --> 17:52.321
Yes. I feel he wants
to crush me.

17:54.239 --> 17:55.783
No further questions.

18:06.585 --> 18:08.337
- What are you doing?
- I want to try something.

18:08.337 --> 18:10.339
We talked about this.
We need to establish--

18:10.339 --> 18:13.258
You know what I love, Ed?

18:15.219 --> 18:17.012
Quaker Crackels cereal.

18:17.012 --> 18:20.015
I mostly eat 'em right out
of the box, like popcorn.

18:20.015 --> 18:23.435
I've-- I've even taken this
to the movie theater.

18:24.603 --> 18:26.522
Where would I find that
in your store?

18:26.522 --> 18:28.524
Which, uh, which aisle?

18:28.524 --> 18:31.985
- Um, six. (CHUCKLES)
- PERRY: Six.

18:31.985 --> 18:35.823
Interesting. That's, uh,
that's the same as Sunny's.

18:35.823 --> 18:39.159
I'm also a big devotee
of Underwood Deviled Ham.

18:39.159 --> 18:41.370
That makes a good sandwich.
Where would I find that?

18:41.370 --> 18:43.997
- Aisle 12.
- Same as Sunny's again.

18:43.997 --> 18:45.833
And-- And what about the Bromo?

18:45.833 --> 18:47.751
For when the Crackels
on aisle six

18:47.751 --> 18:49.837
and the ham on aisle 12
come back on me?

18:49.837 --> 18:52.881
- Aisle two.
- (CHUCKLES) Just like Sunny's.

18:54.508 --> 18:57.970
Well, that's, uh, that's--
that's three for three.

18:57.970 --> 19:00.973
I mean, that's a batting average
Lou Gehrig would be jealous of.

19:02.224 --> 19:05.727
Mr. Purtell,
do you think Henry Ford

19:05.727 --> 19:07.563
pays his engineers
to invent devices

19:07.563 --> 19:09.231
for his company
and then expects them

19:09.231 --> 19:11.859
to go down the street
and reinvent them

19:11.859 --> 19:13.026
for themselves to sell?

19:13.026 --> 19:15.070
ED: (STAMMERS) No.
(CHUCKLES) It's not like that,

19:15.070 --> 19:17.739
Mr. Mason. Uh, if you knew
anything about markets,

19:17.739 --> 19:20.742
you would know that those were
just logical places

19:20.742 --> 19:22.828
any market would put
those items.

19:22.828 --> 19:24.705
It has nothing to do
with what Sunny Gryce...

19:24.705 --> 19:26.373
(INHALES DEEPLY) ...taught me.

19:26.373 --> 19:28.709
What's the slogan
for Sunny Market?

19:29.835 --> 19:32.170
(INHALES SHARPLY)
"All under one roof."

19:32.170 --> 19:34.339
And for your store?

19:34.339 --> 19:36.425
"Everything under our roof."

19:36.425 --> 19:39.344
Well, thank you for changing
those few letters.

19:39.344 --> 19:40.470
MR. KELLARD: Your Honor!

19:40.470 --> 19:42.264
That's because I came up
with the one for Sunny's.

19:42.264 --> 19:44.600
While you were an employee
at Mr. Gryce's store,

19:44.600 --> 19:46.685
you were compensated
for everything you did

19:46.685 --> 19:49.313
with the understanding
that you were doing it

19:49.313 --> 19:50.397
for Sunny Market.

19:50.397 --> 19:54.026
Objection. Now it's Mr. Mason
who is testifying.

19:54.026 --> 19:55.235
Sustained.

19:57.321 --> 20:00.991
Mr. Purtell, can you recognize
in this photograph

20:01.742 --> 20:03.869
where and what this is?

20:03.869 --> 20:06.455
Yes, that-- that's my office
in my store.

20:06.455 --> 20:07.539
How do you have that?

20:07.539 --> 20:09.583
If you look
at this enlarged photograph,

20:09.583 --> 20:12.878
can you read the title
on the spine of the binder?

20:15.339 --> 20:16.924
I didn't steal from him!

20:17.841 --> 20:18.967
Actually, that's not the title.

20:18.967 --> 20:21.303
The title is, "Sunny Market
Manager's Handbook."

20:21.303 --> 20:23.388
Your Honor, I'd like
to submit this into evidence,

20:23.388 --> 20:25.766
- Exhibit D.
- I have that because I wrote it.

20:25.766 --> 20:27.684
- I wrote it!
- PERRY: And you were paid for it

20:27.684 --> 20:29.561
by a man who expected you
to be loyal enough

20:29.561 --> 20:31.813
not to steal it
for your own purposes.

20:33.565 --> 20:38.111
♪ (SOFT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

20:40.030 --> 20:41.114
(SIGHS)

20:42.866 --> 20:44.576
No further questions,
Your Honor.

20:44.576 --> 20:45.619
ED: No, that's not--

20:45.619 --> 20:47.829
(SCOFFS) That's--
Those are my ideas.

20:47.829 --> 20:50.290
He stole from me!
He stole from me!

20:50.290 --> 20:52.542
Can't you see that?
He's trying to ruin me.

20:52.542 --> 20:54.252
This isn't fair! How did you get

20:54.252 --> 20:55.629
- in my office anyway?
- (GAVEL POUNDING)

20:55.629 --> 20:57.339
- JUDGE: Mr. Purtell--
- ED: This isn't right.

20:57.339 --> 21:00.342
Mr. Purtell, you may step down.

21:09.393 --> 21:11.520
DELLA: What was the point
of me staying up all night,

21:11.520 --> 21:13.855
researching, just so you could
toss it all away

21:13.855 --> 21:15.023
and do whatever you wanted?

21:15.023 --> 21:17.734
I'm pretty sure what I just did
won the case for us.

21:17.734 --> 21:18.902
Did you see the jury's faces

21:18.902 --> 21:20.153
when I showed them
that photograph?

21:20.153 --> 21:21.822
You sure they weren't just
reacting to the blood

21:21.822 --> 21:23.824
on your pants? What did you do?

21:25.283 --> 21:27.327
I-- I slipped on the bike
last night on the way home.

21:27.327 --> 21:28.662
- On the way home?
- Yeah.

21:28.662 --> 21:30.956
You were supposed to sell
that thing five months ago

21:30.956 --> 21:32.499
when that degenerate used it
to pay us.

21:32.499 --> 21:34.876
The guy was in trouble,
and he needed a lawyer.

21:34.876 --> 21:36.461
- It's all he had.
- He was a thief.

21:36.461 --> 21:38.880
- He was feeding his family!
- By stealing motorcycles!

21:38.880 --> 21:40.173
- It's stolen.
- It's fun.

21:40.173 --> 21:42.634
Yeah, I've had a wonderful time
with it.

21:44.261 --> 21:47.889
Shit, we have a meeting
with a potential client.

21:47.889 --> 21:49.349
I guess you're not coming now.

21:49.349 --> 21:51.226
It's fine by me.
I'm not hungry anyway.

21:55.605 --> 21:57.649
BROOKS: The hardships
you have all suffered

21:57.649 --> 22:00.819
- are unimaginable.
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

22:00.819 --> 22:02.738
BROOKS: But your spirit
can't be broken,

22:02.738 --> 22:05.991
and we will do all that we can
to make sure it never is broken.

22:05.991 --> 22:08.452
When there is a need,
we will fill it,

22:08.452 --> 22:10.203
which is why
we're moving forward with plans

22:10.203 --> 22:13.290
to open five more
McCutcheon relief kitchens

22:13.290 --> 22:14.374
like this one.

22:14.374 --> 22:17.586
- (CROWD APPLAUDING)
- (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

22:17.586 --> 22:20.255
BROOKS: But this terrible time
will soon pass.

22:20.255 --> 22:23.800
Better days lay ahead
for you and your families

22:23.800 --> 22:25.218
and for this great city.

22:26.178 --> 22:28.346
And that's why I thought today

22:28.346 --> 22:31.141
would be the perfect time
to make a surprise announcement.

22:31.141 --> 22:32.976
Bake, step up here.

22:32.976 --> 22:35.228
Now, you all know old
St. Louis Cardinals' pitcher,

22:35.228 --> 22:36.438
Bake Matthews, right?

22:36.438 --> 22:41.693
- (APPLAUSE)
- (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

22:41.693 --> 22:44.154
- How's that arm, Bake?
- It's good. It's good.

22:44.154 --> 22:45.947
Ready to put it
to work ladling soup, I hope?

22:45.947 --> 22:47.616
Oh, you betcha!

22:47.616 --> 22:49.409
BROOKS: Now, I asked Bake
to join me

22:49.409 --> 22:53.080
because I am announcing today
that I am bringing this city

22:53.080 --> 22:55.582
its very own major league
baseball team,

22:55.582 --> 23:00.629
- playing at McCutcheon Stadium!
- (CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

23:00.629 --> 23:01.755
BROOKS: And what's that mean?

23:01.755 --> 23:03.632
Why, it means jobs
for one thing.

23:03.632 --> 23:06.468
But more than that,
it means this city matters.

23:06.468 --> 23:08.762
It means rooting for fellas
with this city's name

23:08.762 --> 23:10.972
across their chests.
The city you built.

23:10.972 --> 23:12.849
The city that belongs to you.

23:12.849 --> 23:15.769
And the team
that will belong to you!

23:15.769 --> 23:19.356
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

23:19.356 --> 23:22.359
Lydell, would you care
to say anything?

23:23.443 --> 23:26.071
I'm not nearly as eloquent
as my son.

23:26.071 --> 23:28.490
Plus, I think the soup
is getting cold.

23:28.490 --> 23:30.408
(CROWD LAUGHS)

23:30.408 --> 23:32.953
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

23:35.080 --> 23:36.164
BROOKS: Thank you.

23:37.707 --> 23:40.293
The team's really a sealed deal?

23:40.293 --> 23:42.295
I told you I'd do it, Dad.

23:42.295 --> 23:44.506
Yeah. We need
to get going, Lydell.

23:47.092 --> 23:52.722
- ♪ (SOFT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

24:17.664 --> 24:19.166
- So?
- (SIGHS)

24:19.166 --> 24:21.042
Just letting you know...
(INHALES DEEPLY)

24:21.042 --> 24:23.378
...there's been a little bit
of chatter around the department

24:23.378 --> 24:24.713
about the Luxe.

24:24.713 --> 24:27.340
And they've assigned a few dicks
to interview other boat owners.

24:27.340 --> 24:29.342
- So in case that happens--
- I can handle it.

24:31.261 --> 24:33.388
(INHALES DEEPLY)
In case that happens...

24:34.389 --> 24:36.391
you say nothing more
than you need to.

24:36.391 --> 24:38.560
All right, don't try
to outsmart them.

24:38.560 --> 24:39.978
Make sure you get their names.

24:39.978 --> 24:42.272
You see the ads I put
in <i>The Times</i> and <i>The Examiner?</i>

24:42.272 --> 24:43.815
I told them to put
it right under the story

24:43.815 --> 24:46.985
of the Luxe fire. Our place
is gonna be packed tonight.

24:48.528 --> 24:49.446
I hope so.

24:49.446 --> 24:51.323
BROOKS: Holcomb,
this is going to work.

24:52.616 --> 24:53.783
It is working.

24:54.868 --> 24:56.203
What if it doesn't?

24:56.203 --> 24:58.371
I mean, this isn't just
like taking up tennis for me.

24:58.371 --> 24:59.956
I've got my whole life savings
wrapped up

24:59.956 --> 25:02.209
- in this fucking thing.
- Yeah, but don't tell me

25:02.209 --> 25:04.085
you don't enjoy the perks
of being the muscle

25:04.085 --> 25:07.589
in an upscale place instead
of just arresting drunks

25:07.589 --> 25:10.800
- or busting whore houses.
- Not just muscle...

25:12.010 --> 25:13.094
partner.

25:14.846 --> 25:18.516
Right. Listen, the next time
I ask you and your boys

25:18.516 --> 25:22.270
to sabotage a ship,
it's probably smarter

25:22.270 --> 25:25.565
to do it during the day
when there's fewer people.

25:25.565 --> 25:27.817
- ♪ (TENSE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
- BROOKS: Hmm?

25:29.611 --> 25:30.737
I'll see you tonight.

25:35.492 --> 25:36.910
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- My husband first got

25:36.910 --> 25:40.247
in the coil spring game
with his brothers back in '16.

25:40.247 --> 25:42.540
But that's when they were
just making tension springs

25:42.540 --> 25:43.917
for upholstered furniture.

25:43.917 --> 25:47.671
They did the theater seats
at the Fox Theater in Westwood.

25:47.671 --> 25:49.339
- Exciting.
- MRS. HUNT: But there's been

25:49.339 --> 25:51.967
a falling out with my husband
and his brothers,

25:51.967 --> 25:53.385
and so we're splitting off.

25:53.385 --> 25:54.970
We're going
to be making volute springs,

25:54.970 --> 25:58.223
which are for heavy machinery.
With this depression,

25:58.223 --> 26:00.016
people are holding
onto their furniture.

26:00.016 --> 26:01.476
So volute springs
just make sense.

26:01.476 --> 26:02.769
But it is a very different kind

26:02.769 --> 26:04.562
of spring,
as I'm sure you can imagine.

26:04.562 --> 26:06.231
It seems like
a very interesting business.

26:06.231 --> 26:09.985
It is. But it also means
different clients

26:09.985 --> 26:12.737
and very different language
in our new contracts.

26:12.737 --> 26:15.365
I'm sure our firm will be more
than capable of handling those.

26:15.365 --> 26:16.950
MRS. HUNT: Have you ever seen
a volute spring?

26:16.950 --> 26:19.661
I brought a sample with me.
They're quite something.

26:21.121 --> 26:23.540
- It's beautiful.
- MRS. HUNT: (CHUCKLES) Isn't it?

26:24.791 --> 26:27.002
Would you excuse me
for just a moment?

26:27.002 --> 26:29.337
- I have to go powder my nose.
- Oh, of course.

26:29.337 --> 26:31.464
DELLA: I can't wait to take
another look at those springs...

26:31.464 --> 26:32.757
- (LAUGHS)
- DELLA: ...when I get back.

26:32.757 --> 26:36.303
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- ♪ (SOFT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

26:43.268 --> 26:44.352
They'll be there soon.

27:10.253 --> 27:12.672
(DOOR OPENING, CLOSING)

27:23.266 --> 27:25.226
There's a back way out of here,
you know?

27:25.894 --> 27:27.562
Excuse me?

27:27.562 --> 27:29.481
Well, I was thinking
I could go back out there

27:29.481 --> 27:31.358
and tell that flat tire
you've been avoiding

27:31.358 --> 27:33.026
that you got wise and took off.

27:33.026 --> 27:37.364
(CHUCKLES) We need the business.

27:37.364 --> 27:39.491
- I have to charm her.
- ANITA ST. PIERRE: Mm.

27:41.368 --> 27:43.912
Well, you look like
you got a fair bit to spare.

27:45.997 --> 27:48.541
I tell you what, I go
back inside, I yell, "Fire!"

27:48.541 --> 27:50.251
And we just clear
the whole place out.

27:50.251 --> 27:52.837
(LAUGHS)
That'd just get you arrested.

27:52.837 --> 27:55.465
True. But we could steal
some sweets off the dessert cart

27:55.465 --> 27:58.343
- as we make our escape.
- That'd also get you arrested.

27:58.343 --> 28:01.554
Well, sharing the chocolate cake
with you can make it worth it.

28:03.181 --> 28:07.352
- (DOOR OPENING, CLOSING)
- (FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

28:20.198 --> 28:21.616
I should get back.

28:24.661 --> 28:28.873
But if you, uh, see me dozing,
maybe try that fire line.

28:30.083 --> 28:33.503
I do have one more scenario
kicking around.

28:34.587 --> 28:35.713
What's that?

28:36.423 --> 28:37.465
ANITA: Okay.

28:38.758 --> 28:39.884
You go back inside,

28:39.884 --> 28:42.804
and you keep on walking
right out to my big, shiny car.

28:42.804 --> 28:45.432
I take us to a great
little dance joint I know.

28:45.432 --> 28:46.641
We split a bottle of anything--

28:46.641 --> 28:48.643
- I...
- ANITA: Oh, she can't hear us.

28:48.643 --> 28:50.437
- It's--
- No, it's just...

28:51.855 --> 28:52.814
What?

28:54.691 --> 28:56.526
I'm already involved
with someone.

28:57.235 --> 28:58.361
Oh.

28:59.612 --> 29:02.407
Well, is she in good health,
or do I got to wait it out?

29:02.407 --> 29:05.076
(CHUCKLES)

29:05.076 --> 29:07.912
You and I will probably
both be in support hose

29:07.912 --> 29:10.957
- before she has a gray hair.
- ANITA: Mm-hmm.

29:10.957 --> 29:13.168
Well, I tell you what,
if you do ever decide

29:13.168 --> 29:16.045
that you're ready to move on
from cradle robbing

29:16.045 --> 29:18.006
and you need
another escape plan...

29:18.006 --> 29:23.094
♪ (SOFT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

29:34.981 --> 29:37.150
LICK: And maybe
it's the Cardinals coming.

29:37.150 --> 29:39.444
Huh? Huh?
It sure won't be the Yankees.

29:39.444 --> 29:41.571
Ain't none of us
gonna be playing for 'em.

29:41.571 --> 29:43.823
So, I ain't going until
the Homestead Grays show up

29:43.823 --> 29:45.492
with Cool Papa Bell
behind the plate.

29:45.492 --> 29:46.784
You'll be waiting
a long damn time

29:46.784 --> 29:48.828
'cause ain't none of our teams
are coming out this far.

29:48.828 --> 29:49.996
Yeah, you got a point.

29:49.996 --> 29:51.498
LICK: Hell, the rest
of the country don't even know

29:51.498 --> 29:54.334
- there's Colored folk out here.
- (BOTH LAUGH)

29:54.334 --> 29:56.419
That's why White folks
are still showing up.

29:56.419 --> 29:59.631
- (LAUGHS)
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

29:59.631 --> 30:04.469
♪ (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

30:11.226 --> 30:12.810
- Clara.
- CLARA DRAKE: Mm?

30:15.104 --> 30:16.940
Paul, you haven't worked
in weeks.

30:16.940 --> 30:18.900
That man used
to keep you top of mind.

30:18.900 --> 30:20.276
You should've asked me.

30:20.276 --> 30:22.278
And you should've
invited him yourself.

30:33.873 --> 30:35.083
PERRY: Happy birthday.

30:36.793 --> 30:38.253
Thank you.

30:38.253 --> 30:40.588
You know, my dad used
to bring us down here

30:40.588 --> 30:43.591
when we were kids,
so he could catch catfish.

30:43.591 --> 30:45.802
- Over in Watts?
- PERRY: Yeah.

30:45.802 --> 30:49.222
Yeah. We used to try catching
out of that swampy water too.

30:49.222 --> 30:50.765
(DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE)

30:50.765 --> 30:52.392
- This your place?
- No, no, no.

30:52.392 --> 30:54.310
That's my--
my brother-in-law's.

30:55.937 --> 30:58.481
It's temporary.
And it's good for Lucius,

30:58.481 --> 31:01.025
having all this family around,
these helping hands.

31:01.025 --> 31:02.735
- Sure.
- (BALL THUDS)

31:04.862 --> 31:06.531
CHILD: Thank you.

31:06.531 --> 31:08.950
The pictures you took
at Purtell's Market last month

31:08.950 --> 31:10.201
really worked out.

31:12.662 --> 31:15.081
Paul, I'm so sorry
there hasn't been more work.

31:15.081 --> 31:18.585
Hmm. Lot less call for my skill
with civil cases.

31:20.253 --> 31:21.588
(SIGHS)

31:24.382 --> 31:26.217
Come on, what are you doing?

31:26.217 --> 31:27.969
I just thought
a little extra might help.

31:27.969 --> 31:29.220
I don't earn it,
I don't want it.

31:29.220 --> 31:30.638
Come on, y'all.
Time for the cake.

31:31.514 --> 31:33.099
PAUL'S NIECE:
Uncle Paul, come on.

31:35.018 --> 31:40.940
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you
Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

31:40.940 --> 31:47.405
<i>♪ Happy birthday, dear Paul
Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

31:47.405 --> 31:48.615
SPEAKER: Happy birthday!

31:48.615 --> 31:50.408
- CLARA: Make a wish now.
- MORRIS: Happy birthday, Paul!

31:50.408 --> 31:54.787
(ALL CHEER, APPLAUD)

31:54.787 --> 31:56.956
- What'd you wish for?
- A bigger cake.

31:56.956 --> 31:59.917
- (ALL LAUGH)
- Okay, plates.

31:59.917 --> 32:01.085
PEARL: Ooh, okay.

32:01.085 --> 32:03.838
Oh, can you pass down
those forks too? Thank you.

32:04.922 --> 32:06.507
- Grab those.
- Who wants some cornbread?

32:06.507 --> 32:08.676
- Okay, so we just--
- 'Cause the cake is all mine,

32:08.676 --> 32:09.969
so somebody better eat
that cornbread.

32:09.969 --> 32:11.304
- (ALL LAUGH)
- That's a really big...

32:12.388 --> 32:18.478
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

32:18.478 --> 32:21.314
SINGERS: <i>♪ You always save money
At Sunny's! ♪</i>

32:21.314 --> 32:30.073
<i>♪ You always save money
At Sunny's! ♪</i>

32:30.073 --> 32:31.699
- (ALL HUM)
- Hello, Los Angeles.

32:31.699 --> 32:32.909
I'm Sunny Gryce.

32:32.909 --> 32:35.995
Yes, you will save money
at Sunny Market.

32:35.995 --> 32:38.956
During these tough times,
we keep our prices low

32:38.956 --> 32:41.209
to keep your pantry piled high.

32:41.209 --> 32:43.169
Everything you need
is right here.

32:43.169 --> 32:44.962
Just listen to what we have.

32:44.962 --> 32:48.716
Fresh produce, canned goods,
ten choice cuts of meat,

32:48.716 --> 32:50.218
delicious frozen confections,

32:50.218 --> 32:52.053
- all under one roof.
- (SINGERS CONTINUE HUMMING)

32:52.053 --> 32:53.554
SUNNY GRYCE:
Come down to our honey

32:53.554 --> 32:54.889
of a store for yourself.

32:54.889 --> 32:59.227
Guarantee, when you check out,
you too will be singing...

32:59.227 --> 33:08.111
<i>♪ You always save money
At Sunny's! ♪</i>

33:08.111 --> 33:10.196
<i>♪ It's all under one roof! ♪</i>

33:10.196 --> 33:11.823
And that's the truth.

33:12.990 --> 33:15.660
- SUNNY: What do you got?
- PERRY: Purtell wants to settle.

33:15.660 --> 33:17.203
He'll change his store's layout,

33:17.203 --> 33:19.205
give you approval over it,
and drop his slogan.

33:19.205 --> 33:20.581
We also negotiated a settlement

33:20.581 --> 33:23.376
of 5,000 dollars for damages
and infringement.

33:23.376 --> 33:24.585
Five grand?

33:24.585 --> 33:26.754
DELLA: Mr. Purtell doesn't even
have that right now.

33:26.754 --> 33:27.755
We did a full audit.

33:27.755 --> 33:29.173
But we worked out
a payment schedule

33:29.173 --> 33:31.634
- to get your money in full.
- SUNNY: You know who settles?

33:31.634 --> 33:33.511
People who know
they're gonna lose.

33:33.511 --> 33:34.971
People who lost their nerve.

33:34.971 --> 33:37.140
At a moment like that,
you can break a man.

33:37.140 --> 33:39.767
I think I just heard
Ed Purtell crack wide open.

33:39.767 --> 33:42.228
There's really no need
to break him any further.

33:42.228 --> 33:44.897
I mean, the man did work
for you for many years.

33:44.897 --> 33:46.649
Were you in the war, Mason?

33:49.485 --> 33:50.528
Yes. France.

33:50.528 --> 33:52.071
SUNNY: So, then
you and I both know firsthand,

33:52.071 --> 33:53.865
mercy is not something
people can afford

33:53.865 --> 33:55.992
- when they're in a war.
- It's a supermarket,

33:55.992 --> 33:57.243
not the Battle of the Marne,

33:57.243 --> 33:59.203
- and this is a good deal.
- SUNNY: Not to me it's not.

33:59.203 --> 34:01.831
I'm fighting for my life,
and I need fighters by my side.

34:01.831 --> 34:03.666
Now, I thought
you were that man,

34:03.666 --> 34:05.960
but maybe I was wrong
because fighters kill.

34:05.960 --> 34:08.045
You don't seem to have it
in you to finish the job.

34:08.045 --> 34:09.881
Do I have
to find another fighter?

34:11.132 --> 34:13.968
No, no, I can--
I can finish the job.

34:13.968 --> 34:15.094
Good.

34:16.345 --> 34:17.597
Ladies, back to work.

34:19.932 --> 34:22.477
♪ (MID TEMPO MUSIC PLAYING
OVER RADIO) ♪

34:22.477 --> 34:24.145
- MORRIS' DAUGHTER: Daddy.
- PEARL: Hey, hey, hey.

34:24.145 --> 34:26.105
- MORRIS' DAUGHTER: Daddy.
- Don't be bothering your father.

34:26.105 --> 34:29.776
Don't be touching him neither.
Uh, boots off, Morris!

34:29.776 --> 34:34.113
- I got ya. I got ya.
- Hey, Mo. How did it go today?

34:34.113 --> 34:36.324
(EXHALES SHARPLY)
They nearly killed us out there.

34:36.324 --> 34:37.867
PEARL: Mm, them Serbs
out there again.

34:37.867 --> 34:40.620
(SCOFFS) You know it.
Kicking all our tails. You know,

34:40.620 --> 34:42.371
them big fuckers don't know
how to go slow.

34:42.371 --> 34:43.915
Mo, language.

34:49.003 --> 34:51.088
- (LUCIUS DRAKE CRYING)
- I got it.

34:52.590 --> 34:53.800
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

34:53.800 --> 34:55.510
PEARL: Ooh,
that might be Mrs. Steinberg.

34:55.510 --> 34:57.178
Said she'd be by
with new patterns for me

34:57.178 --> 34:59.138
- and Clara to sew.
- (DOOR OPENING)

35:01.057 --> 35:02.350
PEARL: Can I help you?

35:02.350 --> 35:05.228
Yeah, I'm looking
for that man right there.

35:05.228 --> 35:08.105
Come on. Come on.

35:08.105 --> 35:10.191
You want to invite
your friend in, Paul?

35:13.236 --> 35:14.654
PAUL DRAKE: I got this, Pearl.

35:17.949 --> 35:19.158
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

35:21.202 --> 35:22.787
I didn't mean
to bust up suppertime.

35:25.248 --> 35:26.499
What are you doing here?

35:34.298 --> 35:36.300
Mason said you might be looking
for some work.

35:37.802 --> 35:40.221
Melvin Perkins.
You know who that is?

35:41.472 --> 35:43.474
Nigger King of Central Avenue?

35:43.474 --> 35:45.184
Owns The Birch Hotel.

35:45.184 --> 35:48.563
Owns the <i>L.A. Register,</i>
that's the Colored newspaper.

35:48.563 --> 35:50.147
PETE STRICKLAND:
And a few other interests

35:50.147 --> 35:51.399
a little less above board.

35:52.108 --> 35:53.317
But you knew that.

35:55.069 --> 35:57.029
We're hearing down
at the DA's office rumblings

35:57.029 --> 35:58.739
of someone wanting
to take him out.

35:59.615 --> 36:01.492
- Who?
- PETE: Don't know.

36:01.492 --> 36:04.453
A whisper to someone
to someone. I ain't privy.

36:04.453 --> 36:06.122
But Burger
don't want it happening.

36:06.122 --> 36:08.332
He wants to suss out
who's looking to do it,

36:08.332 --> 36:11.168
- so he wants eyes on Perkins.
- Why me?

36:12.044 --> 36:13.713
Perkins operates out
of The Birch.

36:15.172 --> 36:17.258
And it's a Colored hotel.

36:17.258 --> 36:20.428
We need to know his comings
and goings. Friends, enemies.

36:20.428 --> 36:22.555
Who's watching him.
Who might have a beef.

36:22.555 --> 36:23.973
Sorts of dealings
might be getting him

36:23.973 --> 36:25.433
in a jackpot
with the wrong types.

36:25.433 --> 36:26.684
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

36:26.684 --> 36:29.020
You report back
to us what you see,

36:29.020 --> 36:30.354
help us keep him standing.

36:30.354 --> 36:33.149
DA's willing to pay eight bucks
a day plus expenses.

36:34.066 --> 36:35.359
That sound good to you?

36:37.194 --> 36:38.362
Sounds good.

36:47.330 --> 36:48.456
PETE: Evening.

36:49.498 --> 36:50.917
JUDGE: <i>The jury in the matter</i>

36:50.917 --> 36:55.296
of Gryce vs. Purtell find
in favor of the plaintiff,

36:55.296 --> 36:56.631
Sunny Gryce.

36:56.631 --> 36:59.675
It is the judgment
of this court to award Mr. Gryce

36:59.675 --> 37:02.845
the full amount
of 50,000 dollars.

37:04.221 --> 37:06.849
- May I speak, Your Honor?
- Counsel.

37:06.849 --> 37:09.894
Mr. Purtell doesn't have
the financial means

37:09.894 --> 37:12.563
to pay anything even close
to that amount.

37:12.563 --> 37:15.900
His net assets are less
than 500 dollars.

37:15.900 --> 37:18.444
He couldn't pay Mr. Gryce
in a lifetime.

37:23.032 --> 37:24.700
(WHISPERS)
You're absolutely sure?

37:27.787 --> 37:31.958
Um, Your Honor,
my client isn't unsympathetic

37:31.958 --> 37:34.835
to Mr. Purtell's plight.
He certainly doesn't want

37:34.835 --> 37:39.298
to see the defendant ruined
by this enormous debt. And so...

37:40.591 --> 37:42.843
Mr. Gryce is generously offering

37:42.843 --> 37:45.596
to forego the debt owed
to him in exchange...

37:46.722 --> 37:49.767
for Mr. Purtell signing
over his store...

37:49.767 --> 37:53.521
- to Mr. Gryce.
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

37:57.149 --> 37:58.818
- JUDGE: Mr. Kellard?
- (WHISPERS) I'm sorry.

37:58.818 --> 38:04.865
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

38:14.750 --> 38:16.210
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- Thanks.

38:20.089 --> 38:24.635
Come on. I feel like we should--
we should toast to something.

38:26.262 --> 38:27.346
To EB.

38:28.347 --> 38:30.516
- He'd be proud of us.
- Would he?

38:30.516 --> 38:32.643
He'd think
you were a crackerjack lawyer.

38:32.643 --> 38:34.895
More like a vulture
picking the last scraps

38:34.895 --> 38:36.188
off Ed Purtell's bones.

38:36.188 --> 38:37.898
DELLA: I didn't like
what Sunny asked us

38:37.898 --> 38:39.150
to do any more than you.

38:39.150 --> 38:41.402
But the jury decided
that case, not us.

38:41.402 --> 38:43.904
What's gonna happen
to that poor bastard?

38:43.904 --> 38:45.865
Who's to blame
for what happens after?

38:45.865 --> 38:48.284
Well, well. You two look like

38:48.284 --> 38:50.536
you're in that picture
<i>Mata Hari,</i>

38:50.536 --> 38:52.913
hiding away in this back corner.

38:52.913 --> 38:55.833
- Garbo was having more fun.
- PERRY: Mm.

38:55.833 --> 38:57.918
Heard you won. Congratulations.

38:57.918 --> 39:02.673
Yeah. We ran a man
out of business. Hip hooray.

39:02.673 --> 39:04.383
HAMILTON BURGER:
You know what your problem is,

39:04.383 --> 39:05.718
- Mason?
- (SCOFFS)

39:05.718 --> 39:09.221
- Hamilton, now is not the time.
- No, no. Ham, enlighten me.

39:09.221 --> 39:10.431
This isn't going to help.

39:10.431 --> 39:13.517
It's that despite all of your...

39:13.517 --> 39:15.436
- brooding cynicism...
- (PERRY SCOFFS)

39:15.436 --> 39:17.313
...you still believe in justice.

39:17.313 --> 39:20.649
And you don't? You're the DA,
for Christ's sake.

39:20.649 --> 39:23.736
You work in a building
called the Hall of Justice.

39:23.736 --> 39:25.905
A huge, impressive building

39:25.905 --> 39:28.240
built to look like
it's been there 500 years.

39:28.240 --> 39:31.118
Been there six. Don't you know
what we're selling by now?

39:31.118 --> 39:32.203
There is no true justice.

39:32.203 --> 39:34.246
There's only
the illusion of justice.

39:34.246 --> 39:35.956
The illusion of justice?

39:35.956 --> 39:38.209
The fantasy that keeps
people believing

39:38.209 --> 39:40.836
that truth always prevails.

39:40.836 --> 39:43.714
Bad guys get caught.
Good guys put 'em away.

39:43.714 --> 39:45.966
Why are you
the district attorney?

39:45.966 --> 39:49.512
Or are you just the illusion
of the district attorney?

39:49.512 --> 39:51.639
HAMILTON: 'Cause
I'm the hero of that story.

39:51.639 --> 39:53.891
And as long as people
still believe in justice

39:53.891 --> 39:57.770
and there's a system in place
that looks like it works,

39:57.770 --> 40:00.189
I'm doing what the city
pays me to do.

40:01.899 --> 40:03.150
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

40:04.193 --> 40:07.363
Who the fuck wants to be
any part of that?

40:11.534 --> 40:12.743
(SIGHS)

40:16.205 --> 40:18.457
Does everyone feel
Mason hates them,

40:18.457 --> 40:19.959
or just his friends?

40:21.085 --> 40:22.169
Depends on the day.

40:22.169 --> 40:23.504
HAMILTON: What are you drinking?

40:23.504 --> 40:26.382
- Bourbon, neat.
- Sir, the same.

40:30.094 --> 40:32.012
Your favorite bartender is here.

40:32.012 --> 40:33.597
Oh, is he?

40:33.597 --> 40:36.892
Maybe I should change it
to a dirty martini.

40:36.892 --> 40:39.645
- I see the mood you're in.
- And you?

40:39.645 --> 40:42.189
(LAUGHS) Happier
with the current company.

40:42.189 --> 40:43.274
And you and Hazel?

40:43.274 --> 40:44.650
Everything all right
with you two?

40:44.650 --> 40:48.821
Fine. Uncomplicated and...
(INHALES DEEPLY) ...fine.

40:49.738 --> 40:51.198
But maybe with school and work,

40:51.198 --> 40:54.160
I'm too busy for anything
more complicated right now.

40:54.160 --> 40:59.498
Mm. Sounds like the makings
of an exceptionally dull life,

40:59.498 --> 41:00.833
- Miss Street.
- (CHUCKLES)

41:00.833 --> 41:04.128
- Well done.
- It hasn't all been boring.

41:04.128 --> 41:06.630
There's been a nice surprise
here and there.

41:08.799 --> 41:10.968
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- Clara.

41:10.968 --> 41:13.471
- CLARA: Mm-hmm?
- It's okay to smile.

41:13.471 --> 41:16.932
- (LUCIUS CRIES)
- Move a little to your right.

41:16.932 --> 41:19.727
That's good. Right there,
right there, right there.

41:21.395 --> 41:23.480
CLARA: Baby,
Lucius is getting fussy.

41:23.480 --> 41:25.482
I'm worried he's gonna explode.

41:30.237 --> 41:34.700
He's coming. Move left a little,
just a little. Perfect.

41:34.700 --> 41:41.123
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

41:42.333 --> 41:43.834
CLARA: What's he doing?

41:43.834 --> 41:45.794
It's okay, Clara. It's okay.

41:45.794 --> 41:50.090
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

41:52.843 --> 41:56.013
Okay. Let's just move. Mm-hmm.

41:57.348 --> 41:58.390
(CLARA CLEARS THROAT)

41:59.225 --> 42:01.518
Hey. Hang in there.

42:01.518 --> 42:04.355
- (LUCIUS CRIES)
- CLARA: Mm. Yeah.

42:09.610 --> 42:12.613
- CLARA: Paul.
- Okay, okay, okay.

42:13.697 --> 42:14.907
You can go.

42:16.575 --> 42:19.203
- I'll see you at home.
- Yeah. Okay.

42:19.703 --> 42:20.871
Okay.

42:23.499 --> 42:25.459
- CHARLES: <i>Bang, bang, bang!</i>
- BROOKS: <i>Shoot him, Charles!</i>

42:25.459 --> 42:27.086
- Shoot him!
- CHARLES: Bang, bang, bang!

42:27.086 --> 42:29.129
- Bang, bang, bang.
- Oh, where is he?

42:29.129 --> 42:30.631
- Shoot him, Charles! Oh.
- No.

42:30.631 --> 42:32.675
- (GROANS)
- Oh, no. Oh, no.

42:32.675 --> 42:35.094
Marshall Phillip
just shot your horse.

42:35.094 --> 42:36.262
CHARLES: Can we do it again?

42:36.262 --> 42:37.888
But this time,
I get to shoot you?

42:37.888 --> 42:40.766
(CHUCKLES) Tomorrow.
I have to go out.

42:40.766 --> 42:43.018
- PHILLIP: Okay.
- (BROOKS CHUCKLES)

42:43.018 --> 42:45.062
PHILLIP:
Are you meeting Bake Matthews?

42:45.062 --> 42:47.189
Uh, yep.
Finalizing the particulars

42:47.189 --> 42:49.024
of getting the ball club
moving here.

42:50.109 --> 42:52.319
PHILLIP: Can you get him
to sign my card?

42:52.319 --> 42:53.904
- You shred it, wheat!
- (PHILLIP CHUCKLES)

42:53.904 --> 42:55.698
We should kiss the coin
for luck!

42:55.698 --> 42:58.284
Good idea.
Always does the trick.

43:01.912 --> 43:02.955
(KISSES)

43:03.539 --> 43:05.457
Mm... (KISSES)

43:05.457 --> 43:09.878
- Mm... (KISSES)
- (CHARLES AND PHILLIP LAUGH)

43:09.878 --> 43:11.964
BROOKS:
Okay, up to bed, boys. Go!

43:11.964 --> 43:13.090
(BOTH LAUGH)

43:13.090 --> 43:14.633
- Night, Dad.
- Night.

43:14.633 --> 43:16.093
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

43:20.347 --> 43:25.853
- (DOOR OPENING, CLOSING)
- (KEYS JINGLING)

43:25.853 --> 43:32.234
♪ (MELANCHOLIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

44:09.313 --> 44:10.689
BAKE MATTHEWS:
The broads in Cleveland,

44:10.689 --> 44:13.692
surprisingly attractive.
Always a popular stop.

44:13.692 --> 44:15.486
Pittsburgh, you know,
the odds were good,

44:15.486 --> 44:16.779
but the goods were odd.

44:16.779 --> 44:18.614
That's why the players
would love a team out here.

44:18.614 --> 44:20.783
WALTER CRIPPEN: We went
to every one of 'em, Brooks.

44:20.783 --> 44:22.409
- Every city. No one wants...
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

44:22.409 --> 44:24.536
...to move their baseball team
to Los Angeles.

44:24.536 --> 44:26.205
You showed them
the pictures of the stadium?

44:26.205 --> 44:29.583
- And the model? And the numbers?
- WALTER: Population numbers,

44:29.583 --> 44:31.794
financial numbers.
I gave them everything

44:31.794 --> 44:33.879
but Gloria Swanson's
phone number.

44:33.879 --> 44:35.089
Three whiskies, please.

44:35.089 --> 44:36.882
As your attorney,
as your friend,

44:36.882 --> 44:38.884
- I'm telling you, this idea is--
- BROOKS: You told 'em

44:38.884 --> 44:40.761
we're the fastest growing city
in the world?

44:40.761 --> 44:42.805
- WALTER: They don't care.
- The owners, sure.

44:42.805 --> 44:44.431
But the commissioner,
he must see the benefits.

44:44.431 --> 44:46.183
BAKE: Not a one.
Said no Major League team

44:46.183 --> 44:47.684
would ever play west
of the Mississippi.

44:47.684 --> 44:49.812
To them,
L.A. might as well be Mars.

44:49.812 --> 44:50.979
Fucking dinosaurs.

44:50.979 --> 44:52.481
BAKE: You shouldn't have
promised a team

44:52.481 --> 44:53.565
to those reporters, Brooks.

44:53.565 --> 44:56.985
We're getting a team, Bake.
It's the future!

44:56.985 --> 45:01.532
WALTER: The Yanks, the Cubs,
they get 12,000 fans every game.

45:01.532 --> 45:03.409
No one thinks
we're a baseball town.

45:03.409 --> 45:06.537
Well, I built a giant stadium
to prove that we are.

45:06.537 --> 45:10.374
New York gets three teams.
Chicago, two.

45:10.374 --> 45:13.168
We just need one.
One fucking team.

45:13.168 --> 45:14.378
But people know back East.

45:14.378 --> 45:16.213
BROOKS:
Back East is dog shit, Bake!

45:16.213 --> 45:18.632
This is the perfect city
for baseball!

45:18.632 --> 45:20.134
The whole country's running
to get here,

45:20.134 --> 45:22.052
and they still think
we're some backwater!

45:22.052 --> 45:24.012
We're where everyone wants
to be!

45:24.012 --> 45:27.099
You think anyone dreams
of moving to fucking Cincinnati?

45:29.893 --> 45:36.191
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

45:42.197 --> 45:43.282
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

45:43.282 --> 45:45.075
CLARA: I just need
to brush my teeth.

45:45.075 --> 45:46.368
PAUL: Come on in.

45:47.911 --> 45:49.121
Poor thing.

45:50.080 --> 45:51.498
(CLARA SIGHS)

45:51.498 --> 45:53.917
(INHALES DEEPLY)
Mm. You gonna be long?

45:53.917 --> 45:56.003
PAUL: No, no.
I'll be in bed soon.

45:56.003 --> 45:58.255
- (CLARA SIGHS, GROANS)
- (PAUL SIGHS, GROANS)

46:00.215 --> 46:02.342
Clara, you were right
to invite Mason.

46:04.052 --> 46:06.305
Probably wouldn't have
gotten this gig if you didn't.

46:10.058 --> 46:11.560
I'm gonna make this right.

46:12.769 --> 46:13.770
I know.

46:17.399 --> 46:19.067
How'd they come out?

46:19.067 --> 46:20.777
PAUL: Good. Good. Here.

46:22.070 --> 46:23.155
CLARA: Mm.

46:23.155 --> 46:25.240
- Best one.
- Oh.

46:25.240 --> 46:27.242
- PAUL: She is gorgeous.
- (CLARA CHUCKLES)

46:30.412 --> 46:31.955
- You like it?
- Mm-hmm.

46:33.790 --> 46:35.000
(DOGS BARKING IN DISTANCE)

46:35.000 --> 46:40.130
- (PEN SCRIBBLING)
- (PAGES RUSTLING)

47:12.955 --> 47:15.123
- (LINE TRILLING)
- (PHONE RINGING)

47:15.123 --> 47:19.044
♪ (SOFT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING
OVER RADIO) ♪

47:19.044 --> 47:20.420
Anita St. Pierre's residence.

47:20.420 --> 47:22.256
This is very much
Anita St. Pierre.

47:25.592 --> 47:26.635
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

47:26.635 --> 47:28.095
I tell you what,
I'm gonna count to five,

47:28.095 --> 47:29.846
and if you haven't stated
your business

47:29.846 --> 47:31.431
or made
an impressively lewd comment,

47:31.431 --> 47:33.517
then I'll be forced
to hang up the line.

47:34.726 --> 47:35.852
This is Della...

47:37.479 --> 47:38.480
Street.

47:39.398 --> 47:40.732
Who is Della Street?

47:42.526 --> 47:44.111
We met in a powder room.

47:45.195 --> 47:46.572
<i>You gave me your card.</i>

47:47.990 --> 47:49.283
Well, I've given any number

47:49.283 --> 47:51.243
of cards to women
in powder rooms.

47:52.077 --> 47:54.496
<i>Unless, hmm.</i>

47:54.496 --> 47:57.207
Unless you were
that graceful honey,

47:57.207 --> 48:00.127
about five foot seven
with steel blue eyes

48:00.127 --> 48:02.087
as deep as the Arabian Sea,

48:02.087 --> 48:05.257
<i>then perhaps
I do faintly recall you, yes.</i>

48:05.257 --> 48:06.675
Well, that's a relief.

48:07.884 --> 48:09.845
Because besides
the excellent typeset

48:09.845 --> 48:11.388
of your card,

48:11.388 --> 48:15.225
nothing else about you made much
of an impression on me at all.

48:15.225 --> 48:18.395
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

48:18.395 --> 48:20.689
BAKE: It would've been nice,
team ambassador.

48:20.689 --> 48:22.357
I could've used the bump.

48:22.357 --> 48:24.276
BROOKS: You'll get it, Bake.
We're not out of this.

48:24.276 --> 48:26.069
- WALTER: Brooks.
- We can have the governor

48:26.069 --> 48:27.821
invite them out.
Do a whole tour.

48:27.821 --> 48:30.032
Make it first class.

48:30.032 --> 48:32.409
Have the owners see it all
for themselves.

48:32.409 --> 48:34.494
- Sure.
- Yeah, might turn the trick.

48:35.704 --> 48:39.207
- We'll talk about it.
- (CAR ENGINE REVVING)

48:45.505 --> 48:49.426
- (CAR DOOR CLOSING)
- (CAR ENGINE REVVING)

49:17.412 --> 49:20.374
Oh, shit. Bake. Bake!

49:24.211 --> 49:26.922
- (CAR ENGINE STARTS)
- (GUN COCKING)

49:26.922 --> 49:33.428
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

49:44.106 --> 49:46.316
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

49:46.316 --> 49:49.986
♪ (MELLOW SONG PLAYING
OVER RADIO) ♪

49:58.370 --> 49:59.413
Whatever you want...

50:01.164 --> 50:02.833
you're not paying for it.

50:02.833 --> 50:06.753
Well, it's not legal,
so it doesn't exist anyway,

50:06.753 --> 50:07.963
so what's to pay for?

50:07.963 --> 50:10.549
I'll have a shot of rye.
Thank you.

50:10.549 --> 50:14.052
- (SPEAKS SPANISH)
- Ooh, <i>gracias.</i>

50:15.721 --> 50:17.889
I hate what you've done
with the place.

50:17.889 --> 50:20.392
Well, if you cared so much
about your house,

50:20.392 --> 50:22.102
you wouldn't have left it
a shithole.

50:22.102 --> 50:23.228
(LAUGHS)

50:23.228 --> 50:24.813
LUPE GIBBS:
I made something out of it.

50:24.813 --> 50:27.399
Yeah, probably what I hate most.
I'm not sure how I feel

50:27.399 --> 50:30.569
about a photo of my grandmother
sitting over the bar.

50:31.361 --> 50:33.155
She's our patron saint.

50:33.155 --> 50:35.449
- She looks after the place.
- (CHUCKLES)

50:37.409 --> 50:40.328
LUPE: Come on.
You never really like it here.

50:40.328 --> 50:42.664
And by the time you left,
you didn't like me much either.

50:42.664 --> 50:44.458
So, what brings you back?

50:46.001 --> 50:48.253
A lot of places I don't want
to be these days.

50:48.253 --> 50:50.589
Tonight, this felt
like the least of them.

51:01.141 --> 51:02.601
Always a black cloud.

51:06.772 --> 51:07.773
(SCOFFS)

51:07.773 --> 51:10.108
LUPE: Remember about that place
I told you once,

51:10.108 --> 51:14.279
on the tip of Baja Mexico?
Cabo San Lucas.

51:14.279 --> 51:17.449
It's a little nothing town,
but it could be great.

51:17.449 --> 51:20.076
I can fly people in two stops.

51:20.076 --> 51:22.537
I bought a big piece of land. Cheap.

51:23.538 --> 51:25.665
Whose farm did you steal
to get that?

51:28.210 --> 51:29.252
<i>Gracias.</i>

51:31.213 --> 51:33.465
I start with a runway
